<span id="vi.iv.v.l-p1"></span> <span class="c1"><span
id="vi.iv.v.l-p1.1"></span>Chapter L.—A Satisfactory Answer.</span>

<span id="vi.iv.v.l-p2"></span>Then I, already perceiving the
explanation, smiled, and said that he was a prophet.  And Peter said: 
“If, then, he was a prophet, being a man, he was ignorant of nothing, by
reason of his having received foreknowledge from God; how then, should
He, who gave to man the gift of foreknowledge, being God, Himself be
ignorant?”  And I said:  “You have spoken rightly.”  Then Peter said: 
“Come with me one step further.  It being acknowledged by us that God
foreknows all things, there is every necessity that the scriptures are
false which say that He is ignorant, and those are true which say that
He knows.”  Then said I:  “It must needs be so.”

